This week, decisive action was taken to stabilize the banking system without risking taxpayer dollars. The goal was to protect jobs and small businesses, ensuring that no losses would be borne by the taxpayers. As a result of these actions, the banking system is now more resilient and stable. On Monday, it was emphasized that deposits would be secure for the American people and businesses. Accountability for those responsible for the financial crisis was also highlighted, with a commitment to ensuring that no one is above the law. However, the administration's authority to hold executives responsible is limited by current laws. It is suggested that regulations should make it easier for regulators to recover compensation from executives, impose civil penalties, and ban them from working in the banking industry in the future. Congress is urged to enact stricter penalties for senior bank executives who contribute to the failure of their institutions.